\chapter{Conclusion}
\label{ch:conclusion}

\lettrine[lines=2]{T}{his chapter} synthesizes the contributions of the RCC agent-based model with glucose sensing, discusses its current limitations, and outlines directions for future work.

% ======================================================================
\section{Summary of Contributions}
\label{sec:contributions}

The contributions of this work are organized around four themes: metabolic modeling, biological fidelity, computational infrastructure, and clinical validation.

\paragraph{Metabolic microenvironment modeling.}
A central contribution of this project is the introduction of a continuous three-dimensional glucose concentration field overlaid on the discrete agent grid. Glucose is injected by blood vessel agents, diffuses according to Fick's law, and is consumed by all cell types at rates governed by their metabolic profiles. Tumor cells consume glucose at approximately 200 times the normal rate, consistent with the Warburg effect, creating local depletion zones that suppress immune cell function and viability. Immune cells, in turn, employ glucose gradients for chemotactic navigation when no direct antigenic target is available. This bidirectional coupling between metabolic state and agent behavior introduces a metabolic layer that has been largely absent from prior agent-based models of the tumor microenvironment, and it adds eight new parameters governing glucose dynamics to the model's parameter space.

\paragraph{Biological fidelity.}
The model represents the tumor microenvironment through 18 distinct agent types whose interactions are mediated by an effect system encoding local signaling, cytokine release, and cell-to-cell contact. Tumor genetic heterogeneity is captured by a 16-gene DNA system with codon-level translation, enabling the modeling of clonal evolution, neoantigen generation, and immune evasion through mutation accumulation. Sex-dependent treatment response is modeled explicitly through estrogen, testosterone, and progesterone pathways that modulate immune cell behavior via 17 distinct effect channels, including a biphasic estrogen response curve that captures the nonlinear relationship between hormone concentration and immune activation. Together, these subsystems allow the model to represent biological variability at a granularity that connects molecular-scale events to population-level treatment outcomes.

\paragraph{Computational infrastructure.}
The migration from the Mesa framework to Repast4Py restructures the model's agent hierarchy, spatial indexing, and scheduling to operate within an MPI-based distributed computing environment. This port preserves all 18 agent types and their interaction logic while adapting to Repast4Py's \texttt{Agent}, \texttt{SharedContext}, and \texttt{SharedGrid} abstractions, and it required the development of custom spatial indexing utilities and grid management functions. Parameter optimization is handled by an Optuna-based Bayesian optimization pipeline that searches the 92-parameter space for configurations reproducing clinical observations. A Streamlit-based user interface provides an accessible front end for configuring simulations, executing runs, and visualizing results, lowering the barrier to use for researchers without extensive programming experience.

\paragraph{Clinical validation.}
The integrated model was validated through a 160-simulation study comparing model predictions against data from the ARON-1 clinical trial. Sex-stratified results demonstrated that the model reproduces observed treatment response patterns, with simulated female patients achieving 65\% survival under ICI+TKI combination therapy compared with 55\% for male patients. These results are consistent with the clinical literature on sex-dependent immunotherapy response in RCC and suggest that the explicit modeling of hormonal modulation contributes meaningfully to the model's predictive capacity.

% ======================================================================
\section{Model Limitations}
\label{sec:limitations}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Single-rank execution} — Model operates on single MPI rank, glucose field requires halo exchange for distribution across ranks
    \item \textbf{Simplified glucose dynamics} — Models only glucose with linear diffusion, missing oxygen, lactate, and amino acid coupling
    \item \textbf{Fixed blood vessel topology} — Blood vessels inject glucose at fixed rate regardless of surrounding conditions
    \item \textbf{No spatial immune infiltration patterns} — All immune cells initialized randomly without modeling vascular entry patterns  
    \item \textbf{Simplified TCR matching} — Uses discrete threshold-based comparison rather than continuous binding affinities
    \item \textbf{Deferred multi-rank validation} — SharedContext infrastructure in place but not validated in distributed configurations
\end{itemize}

% ======================================================================
\section{Future Work}
\label{sec:future-work}

\paragraph{Near-term (6--12 months).}
The most immediate priority is multi-rank MPI scaling of the glucose field through domain decomposition and halo exchange, which would allow simulation of larger tissue volumes and higher cell counts than are feasible on a single process. Extending the metabolic system to include oxygen, lactate, and amino acid fields with coupled reaction-diffusion terms would capture the metabolic crosstalk that governs immune cell polarization and tumor acidosis. Additionally, replacing the current fixed blood vessel topology with a dynamic angiogenesis model driven by VEGF gradients would enable the simulation of vascular remodeling in response to tumor growth and anti-angiogenic therapy.

\paragraph{Medium-term (1--2 years).}
Tracking clonal lineage relationships through simulation time would allow the model to study how spatial competition and immune selection pressure shape tumor heterogeneity, a question that is difficult to address with clinical sampling alone. Integrating patient-specific tumor geometry from CT or MRI imaging data would move the model closer to personalized simulation by grounding the initial spatial configuration in individual patient anatomy. Porting computationally intensive components---particularly the glucose diffusion solver and agent interaction calculations---to GPU execution via CuPy or JAX would reduce per-simulation runtime and make large-scale parameter sweeps more practical.

\paragraph{Long-term (2--5 years).}
Prospective integration with clinical trial workflows would require regulatory review and validation against additional trial datasets, but could ultimately enable the use of simulation-derived predictions as a complement to standard clinical decision-making. Adapting the framework to other solid tumors, such as melanoma, non-small-cell lung cancer, and hepatocellular carcinoma, would test the generality of the agent-based architecture and the glucose sensing layer across different tumor microenvironments. A systematic \emph{in silico} screening platform for combination therapies could explore dosing schedules and drug pairings at a scale that is infeasible in clinical trials, while computational biomarker discovery through analysis of high-dimensional simulation output may identify predictive signatures that warrant experimental validation.

% ======================================================================
\section{Clinical Impact}
\label{sec:clinical-impact}

This work contributes to ongoing efforts in computational oncology by demonstrating that mechanistic agent-based models can generate clinically relevant predictions when calibrated against trial data. The integration of metabolic dynamics with immune system modeling provides a framework for investigating why seemingly similar patients respond differently to identical treatments, moving beyond population-level averages toward stratified and, ultimately, individualized treatment modeling. The renal cell carcinoma agent-based model with glucose sensing demonstrates that coupling local metabolic state to immune cell behavior yields measurable improvements in the model's ability to reproduce observed clinical outcomes, providing a foundation for further development in computational precision medicine.

% ======================================================================
\section{Closing Remarks}
\label{sec:closing-remarks}

The four objectives stated in Chapter~\ref{ch:introduction}---porting the model from Mesa to Repast4Py for MPI parallelism, adding a glucose microenvironment sensing layer, validating against ARON-1 clinical data, and optimizing parameters via Bayesian optimization---have each been addressed in this work. The resulting model integrates metabolic, genetic, hormonal, and pharmacological subsystems into a single agent-based framework that reproduces sex-stratified treatment outcomes consistent with clinical observation. While substantial limitations remain, particularly in single-rank execution and metabolic scope, the model establishes an extensible platform on which the future directions outlined above can be pursued.